<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="260">
Diagnosis of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" class="Insecta" evidence="document-1-1" evidenceDetail="p[plau]+p" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" source="D6ECB28283889514C41902DBCAD0BFA7,6570ED897E3DD43889E838B2C3988037,29333B4F4C055F314EFEC9DEDC4229AF" species="rufibarbis" subGenus="Serviformica">Formica (Serviformica) rufibarbis</taxonomicName>
group
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="260">
Within the Palaearctic members of the subgenus Servifor-mica, the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" class="Insecta" evidence="document-1-1" evidenceDetail="combination" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" source="D1DC544E8B50BEEB7783218A84A0B16F,4FE655B041D782DA07AC1A61FF18E422" species="rufibarbis">Formica rufibarbis</taxonomicName>
group (typical example 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forel" authorityYear="1886" class="Insecta" evidence="document-1-1" evidenceDetail="combination" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" source="DA84A2BDD975433DBA4FBF5A47D21E6B,110F509C8F8256860FF6D27C4DAAAFF3" species="clara">F. clara</taxonomicName>
, Figs. 12 and 13) is diagnosable by the following character combination: mesosoma showing 25 to 100% reddish pigmentation; moderate to large body size (nest means of CS 1.075 - 1.731 mm); moderate eye size (nest means of EYE / CS1.4 0.274 - 0.312); posterior margin and underside of head normally without setae (nOCC and nGU may occasionally achieve 1.5 and 3.0 in 
<taxonomicName authority="Seifert &amp; Schultz, 2009" authorityName="Seifert &amp; Schultz" authorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" evidence="newLabel" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" source="C85C0C921E15C704415DA3545AB944CD,A3F01EA5E1A98E22DAC1624D1C10A087" species="anatolica" status="sp. n.">F. anatolica</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species" rankGroup="species" rankGroupNumber="3" rankNumber="3">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
), mesosoma with zero to numerous setae; petiole scale rather wide (nest means of PEW / CS1.4 0.364 - 0.523), with a convex or bluntly angulate dorsal crest; gaster ter-gites with a dense, usually silvery pubescence (sqPDG1.4 2.7 - 3.9) and with more or less dense transverse micro-ripples (RipD1.4 3.8 - 9.2), thus appearing more matt at low magnifications. Range West Europe to East China. Moderately to strongly thermophilic; avoiding the boreal zone; in the temperate climate zone only in open, sun-exposed habitats; in warmer climate zones some species also occurring in woodland. Primary habitats are open grassland, and most species invade rural or suburban areas. Monodomous colonies with single to few queens. Simple, sometimes extended soil nests, frequently under stones, rarely with a flat mound of mineral soil particles or even some organic material. Predacious and trophobiotic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
